One method uses `row_number()`:

    select t.*
    from (select t.*,
                 row_number() over (partition by identifier 
                                    order by (case when record_authority is null then 2 else 1 end), record_authority asc
                                   ) as seqnum
          from t
         ) t
    where seqnum = 1;

Another uses a correlated subquery:

    select t.*
    from t
    where t.record_authority = (select min(t2.record_authority)
                                from t t2
                                where t2.identifier = t.identifier
                               );

Since you&#39;re new to Java, don&#39;t worry about splitting classes into separate files for now. I personally don&#39;t use Eclipse, but what you did is correct. You can add (above or below) a new class in the same file, using the same syntax!

```java
class OtherClass {
   // have your functions and fields here
}

public class classMain {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
    //do stuff
    OtherClass other = new OtherClass();
    }
}
```

You can use, reference, instantiate, and do any number of things with multiple classes in the same file :)

